800-53 I agree with the way you look at certifications. I know that most people like me who are switching careers into cybersecurity or IT in general, see what the employers post that they are looking for in someone and immediately feel like they need these certain certs to even qualify to apply. So a lot of people feel the need to get those certs, but I've seen people that have those certs that have had others picked over them, simply because those people were able to "build up their armor" so they are well rounded instead of just a bunch of certifications to throw on the resume. I've spoken to a guy that has a computer science degree but he confessed he didn't know much when it came to networking, Linux, etc, and that he spent a few years just doing the degree but nothing outside of that. And he found other people with no degree but knew all of those things he didn't actually learn in his classes. So just because you go and get a degree or a certification doesn't mean you'll have it in the bag and can call it a day lol.  By the way Josh, your content is great and helpful and you inspire so many people!
